Definition 20 (fpullback). Let $J:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ be a functor, and $\mathsf{p}:\mathsf{\tilde{U}}\to\mathsf{U}$ a morphism of ${\mathcal{D}}$. Given an object $X$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$ and morphism $f:J(X)\to\mathsf{U}$ in ${\mathcal{D}}$, a $J$-pullback of $\mathsf{p}$ along $f$ consists of an object $X^{\prime}$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$ and morphisms $p^{\prime}:X^{\prime}\to X$ and $Q:J(X^{\prime})\to\mathsf{\tilde{U}}$, such that the following square commutes and is a pullback: $\xymatrix{**[l]J(X^{\prime})\ar[r]^{-}{Q}\ar[d]_{J(p^{\prime})}\ar@{}[dr]|<<{% \text{\pigpenfont A}}&\mathsf{\tilde{U}}\ar[d]^{\mathsf{p}}\\ **[l]J(X)\ar[r]_{f}&\mathsf{U}}$
Definition 11. Let $Y$ be a term-structure and $Z$ a $\mathsf{q}$-morphism structure over $X$. Say that $Y$ and $Z$ are compatible if for all $f:\Gamma\to\Gamma^{\prime}$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, $\mathsf{te}_{f^{*}{A}}=\mathsf{q}({f},{A})^{*}{\mathsf{te}_{A}}$.
Definition 8 (qq_morphism_structure). Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a category equipped with an object extension structure $X$. A (split) $\mathsf{q}$-morphism structure over $X$ consists of: 1. for each $f:\Gamma^{\prime}\to\Gamma$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, a map $\mathsf{q}({f},{A}):{\Gamma}.{A}\to\Gamma$, such that following square commutes and is a pullback $\xymatrix@C=5pc{{\Gamma^{\prime}}.{f^{*}{A}}\ar[r]^{\mathsf{q}({f},{A})}\ar[d]% _{\mathsf{\pi}_{f^{*}{A}}}\ar@{}[dr]|<<{\text{\pigpenfont A}}&{\Gamma}.{A}\ar[% d]^{\mathsf{\pi}_{A}}\\ \Gamma^{\prime}\ar[r]_{f}&\Gamma}$ and such that 2. for each $\Gamma$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, $\mathsf{q}({1_{\Gamma}},{A})=\Delta_{1_{\Gamma}^{*}{A},A}\ :\ {\Gamma}.{1_{% \Gamma}^{*}{A}}\to{\Gamma}.{A}$; and 3. for each $f^{\prime}:\Gamma^{\prime\prime}\to\Gamma^{\prime}$, $f:\Gamma^{\prime}\to\Gamma$, and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, $\mathsf{q}({{f^{\prime}}\cdot{f}},{A})={{\Delta_{({f^{\prime}}\cdot{f})^{*}{A}% ,f^{\prime*}{f^{*}{A}}}}\cdot{\mathsf{q}({f^{\prime}},{f^{*}{A}})}}\cdot{% \mathsf{q}({f},{A})}\ :\ {\Gamma^{\prime\prime}}.{({f^{\prime}}\cdot{f})^{*}{A% }}\to{\Gamma}.{A}.$ Here the suppressed equalities on the $\Delta$ terms come from the functoriality axioms of $\mathsf{Ty}$.
Definition 3 ([Pit00]; typecat_structure, is_split_typecat, split_typecat_structure). A type-category consists of: 0. a category ${\mathcal{C}}$, together with 1. for each object $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}$, a type $\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, 2. for each $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, an object ${\Gamma}.{A}:{\mathcal{C}}$ 3. for each such $\Gamma$, $A$, a morphism $\mathsf{\pi}_{A}:{\Gamma}.{A}\to\Gamma$, 4. for each map $f:\Gamma^{\prime}\to\Gamma$, a ‘reindexing’ function $\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})\to\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma^{\prime}})$, denoted $A\mapsto f^{*}{A}$, 5. for each $\Gamma$, $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, and $f:\Gamma^{\prime}\to\Gamma$, a morphism $\mathsf{q}({f},{A}):{\Gamma^{\prime}}.{f^{*}{A}}\to{\Gamma}.{A}$, 6. such that for each such $\Gamma$, $A$, $\Gamma^{\prime}$, $f$, the following square commutes and is a pullback: $\xymatrix@C=5pc{{\Gamma^{\prime}}.{f^{*}{A}}\ar[r]^{\mathsf{q}({f},{A})}\ar[d]% _{\mathsf{\pi}_{f^{*}{A}}}\ar@{}[dr]|<<{\text{\pigpenfont A}}&{\Gamma}.{A}\ar[% d]^{\mathsf{\pi}_{A}}\\ \Gamma^{\prime}\ar[r]_{f}&\Gamma}$ A type-category is split if: 7. for each $\Gamma$, the type $\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$ is a set; 8. for each $\Gamma$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, we have equalities (a) $e:1_{\Gamma}^{*}{A}=A$, and (b) $\mathsf{q}({1_{\Gamma}},{A})=\Delta_{e}\ :\ {\Gamma}.{1_{\Gamma}^{*}{A}}\to{% \Gamma}.{A}$; and 9. for $f^{\prime}:\Gamma^{\prime\prime}\to\Gamma^{\prime})$, $f:\Gamma^{\prime}\to\Gamma$, and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, we have equalities (a) $e^{\prime}:({f^{\prime}}\cdot{f})^{*}{A}=f^{\prime*}{f^{*}{A}}$, and (b) $\mathsf{q}({{f^{\prime}}\cdot{f}},{A})={{\Delta_{e^{\prime}}}\cdot{\mathsf{q}(% {f^{\prime}},{f^{*}{A}})}}\cdot{\mathsf{q}({f},{A})}\ :\ {\Gamma^{\prime\prime% }}.{({f^{\prime}}\cdot{f})^{*}{A}}\to{\Gamma}.{A}.$
Definition 1 ([Fio12, Appendix]; cwf_structure, cwf). A category with families (à la Fiore) consists of: 0. a category ${\mathcal{C}}$, together with 1. presheaves $\mathsf{Ty},\mathsf{Tm}:{\mathcal{C}}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathsf{Set}$; 2. a natural transformation $\mathsf{p}:\mathsf{Tm}\to\mathsf{Ty}$; and 3. for each object $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, a representation of the fiber of $\mathsf{p}$ over $A$, i.e. (a) an object ${\Gamma}.{A}:{\mathcal{C}}$ and map $\mathsf{\pi}_{A}:{\Gamma}.{A}\to\Gamma$, (b) an element $\mathsf{te}_{A}:\mathsf{Tm}({{\Gamma}.{A}})$, such that $\mathsf{p}_{{\Gamma}.{A}}(\mathsf{te}_{A})=\mathsf{\pi}_{A}^{*}{A}:\mathsf{Tm}% ({\Gamma}.{A}),$ (c) and such that the induced commutative square $\xy\xymatrix{**[l]\mathsf{y}({\Gamma}.{A})\ar[r]^{-}{\widehat{\mathsf{te}_{A}}% }\ar[d]_{\mathsf{y}(\mathsf{\pi}_{A})}\ar@{}[dr]|<<{\text{\pigpenfont A}}&% \mathsf{Tm}\ar[d]^{\mathsf{p}}\\ **[l]\mathsf{y}(\Gamma)\ar[r]_{\widehat{A}}&\mathsf{Ty}}$ is a pullback. (Here e.g. $\widehat{A}$ denotes the Yoneda transpose of an element of a presheaf.) By a CwF structure on a category ${\mathcal{C}}$, we mean the data of items 1–3 above.
Definition 21 (relative_universe, weak_relative_universe). Let $J:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ be a functor, as above. A $J$-universe structure on a map $\mathsf{p}:\mathsf{\tilde{U}}\to\mathsf{U}$ of ${\mathcal{D}}$ is a function giving, for each object $X$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ and map $f:J(X)\to\mathsf{U}$, a $J$-pullback $({X}.{f},\mathsf{p}_{f},\mathsf{Q}({X},{f}))$ of $\mathsf{p}$ along $f$. A universe relative to $J$, or briefly a $J$-relative universe, is a map $\mathsf{p}$ equipped with a $J$-universe structure. A weak universe relative to $J$ is a map $\mathsf{p}:\mathsf{\tilde{U}}\to\mathsf{U}$ such that for all suitable $X$, $f$, there exists some $J$-pullback of $\mathsf{p}$ along $f$.
Definition 5 (term_fun_structure). Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a category equipped with an object extension structure $X$. A (functional) term-structure over $X$ consists of: 1. a presheaf $\mathsf{Tm}:{\mathcal{C}}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathsf{Set}$, and natural transformation $\mathsf{p}:\mathsf{Tm}\to\mathsf{Ty}$; 2. for each object $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, an element $\mathsf{te}_{A}:\mathsf{Tm}({{\Gamma}.{A}})$, such that $({\Gamma}.{A},\mathsf{\pi}_{A},\mathsf{te}_{A})$ form a representation of the fiber of $\mathsf{p}$ over $A$ as in item 3 of Def. 1. One might say functional to distinguish these from familial term-structures, which would correspond analogously to CwF’s in the sense of Dybjer, with $\mathsf{Tm}({\Gamma})$ a family indexed by $\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$. For the present paper, however, we work only with the functional ones, so call these simply term-structures.
Definition 32 (rep_map). A map $\mathsf{p}:\mathsf{Tm}\to\mathsf{Ty}$ of presheaves on a category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is representable if for each for each $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}$ and $A:\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$, there exists some representation of the fiber of $\mathsf{p}$ over $A$, i.e. some $\mathsf{\pi}_{A}:{\Gamma}.{A}\to\Gamma$ and $\mathsf{te}_{A}\in\mathsf{Tm}({{\Gamma}.{A}})$ satisfying the conditions of Definition 1, item 3.2Note that in [Awo16], Awodey takes representable map to mean what we call a CwF structure, i.e. to include choices of representations of the fibers; cf. [Awo16, §1.1, Algebraic character]. In other words, a representable map of presheaves on ${\mathcal{C}}$ is just like a CwF structure, except that the representations are merely assumed to exist, not included as chosen data.
Definition 2. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a CwF, $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}$ an object, and $e:A=B$ an equality of elements of $\mathsf{Ty}({\Gamma})$. We write $\Delta_{e}:{\Gamma}.{A}\cong{\Gamma}.{B}$ for the induced isomorphism $\mathsf{idtoiso}(\mathsf{ap}_{x\mapsto{\Gamma}.{x}}(e))$.
Definition 1.2. Let $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ be full additive subcategories of $\mathcal{B}$ which are closed under direct summands and isomorphisms. We call $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ a cotorsion pair if it satisfies the following conditions. (a) $\mathbb{E}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=0$. (b) For any object $B\in\mathcal{B}$, there exist two conflations $\displaystyle V_{B}\rightarrowtail U_{B}\twoheadrightarrow B,\quad B% \rightarrowtail V^{B}\twoheadrightarrow U^{B}$ satisfying $U_{B},U^{B}\in\mathcal{U}$ and $V_{B},V^{B}\in\mathcal{V}$.
Definition 1.5. A pair of cotorsion pairs $((\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$ on $\mathcal{B}$ is called a twin cotorsion pair if it satisfies $\mathbb{E}(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{V})=0$, or equivalently $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{U}$. Remark that any cotorsion pair $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ gives a twin cotorsion pair $((\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$. Thus a cotorsion pair can be regarded as a special case of a twin cotorsion pair, satisfying $\mathcal{S}=\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{T}=\mathcal{V}$.
Definition 24. A torsion pair of a (co)complete and locally small abelian category $\mathcal{A}$, is a pair $(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ of classes of $\mathcal{A}$ such that: (1) ${\rm Hom}(T,F)=0$ for all $T\in\mathcal{T}$ and $F\in\mathcal{F}$. (2) If ${\rm Hom}(C,F)=0$ for all $F\in\mathcal{F}$, then $C\in\mathcal{T}$. (3) If ${\rm Hom}(T,C)=0$ for all $T\in\mathcal{T}$, then $C\in\mathcal{F}$.
Definition 12. A ring $R$ is left $n$-coherent if $\mathcal{FP}_{n}\subseteq\mathcal{FP}_{n+1}$.
Definition 6. A ring is said to be left $n$-hereditary if every finitely $(n-1)$-presented submodule of a finitely generated projective left module is also a projective module.
Definition 18. Let $R$ be a ring and $n\geq 0$ (including the case $n=\infty$). (1) We say that an $R$-module $M$ is $\text{FP}_{n}$-injective if ${\rm Ext}^{1}_{R}(F,M)=0$ for all $F\in\mathcal{FP}_{n}$. We denote by $\mathcal{FP}_{n}\text{-}{\rm Inj}$ the class of all $\text{FP}_{n}$-injective modules. (2) We say that an $R$-module $M$ is $\text{FP}_{n}$-flat if ${\rm Tor}_{1}^{R}(F,M)=0$ for all $F\in\mathcal{FP}_{n}$. We denote by $\mathcal{FP}_{n}\text{-}{\rm Flat}$ the class of all $\text{FP}_{n}$-flat modules.
Definition 38. The maximal order $\mathcal{A}$ is del Pezzo if $\omega_{\mathcal{A}}^{\vee}$ is ample.
Definition 7. A semiorthogonal decomposition of $\mathcal{T}$ is a sequence $(\mathcal{S}_{1},\dotsc,\mathcal{S}_{n})$ of full triangulated subcategories of $\mathcal{T}$, such that there exists a filtration $0=\mathcal{T}_{0}\subseteq\mathcal{T}_{1}\subseteq\dotsc\subseteq\mathcal{T}_{% n}=\mathcal{T}$ where $\mathcal{T}_{i}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$ is a (left) admissible subcategory such that $\mathcal{S}_{i}\cong\mathcal{T}_{i}/\mathcal{T}_{i-1}$. We will denote this by $\mathcal{T}=\left\langle\mathcal{S}_{1},\dotsc,\mathcal{S}_{n}\right\rangle.$
Definition 15. A fat point module for $A$ is a graded module $F$ satisfying the following properties: 1. $F$ is generated by $F_{0}$ 2. The Hilbert function $\dim_{k}F_{n}$ is a constant $\geq 2$, which is called the multiplicity. 3. $F$ has no nonzero finite-dimensional submodules. 4. $\pi F\in\operatorname{qgr}A$ is simple A fat point is the isomorphism class of a fat point module in $\operatorname{qgr}A$.
Definition 11. Let ${\mathcal{T}}$ be an $\operatorname{Ext}$-finite triangulated category and let $(E,F)$ be an exceptional pair of objects in ${\mathcal{T}}$. We define the left mutation $\operatorname{L}_{E}F$ as the cone of the morphism (since the pair is exceptional, the cone is unique up to unique isomorphism). $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(E,F)\otimes E\rightarrow F\rightarrow% \operatorname{L}_{E}F$ If $\mathbb{E}\coloneqq(E_{1},\ldots E_{n})$ is an exceptional collection in ${\mathcal{T}}$ we define the mutation at $i$ to be the exceptional collection $(E_{1},\ldots,\operatorname{L}_{E_{i}}E_{i+1},E_{i},\ldots,E_{n})$. These mutations can be interpreted as an action of the braid group on $n$ strings, denoted $\mathrm{B}_{n}$, on the set of all exceptional collections. To see this, let $\sigma_{1},\ldots,\sigma_{n-1}$ be the standard generators for $\mathrm{B}_{n}$, then $\sigma_{i}$ acts on an exceptional collection via mutation at $i$, i.e. $\sigma_{i}(\mathbb{E}):=(E_{1},\ldots,\operatorname{L}_{E_{i}}E_{i+1},E_{i},% \ldots,E_{n}).$
Definition 44. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a maximal order on a ruled surface $S\to C$. Then we say that it is half ruled if the fiber of the order over the generic point of $C$ is half ruled.
Definition 36. The canonical sheaf of $\mathcal{A}$ is the $\mathcal{A}$-bimodule $\omega_{\mathcal{A}}:=\mathcal{H}\mathrm{om}_{\mathcal{O}_{S}}(\mathcal{A},% \omega_{S}).$
Definition 2. Let $A$ be a connected graded $k$-algebra. Then we say $A$ is Artin–Schelter regular of dimension $d$ if 1. $\operatorname{gl\,dim}A=d$; 2. $\operatorname{GK\,dim}A=d$; 3. $A$ is Gorenstein (with respect to the integer $d$), i.e. there exists $l\in\mathbb{Z}$ such that $\operatorname{Ext}_{\operatorname{Gr}A}^{i}(k_{A},A)\cong\begin{cases}{}_{A}k(% l)&i=d,\\ 0&i\neq d.\end{cases}$
Definition 42. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a maximal order in a central simple algebra of degree 2 over the function field $K$ of a curve $X$ of genus $0$. If $\mathcal{A}$ is ramified in 3 points, with ramification degree 2 in each point, then we say that $\mathcal{A}$ is half ruled.
Definition 3. An elliptic triple is a triple $(C,\sigma,\mathcal{L})$ where 1. $C$ is a divisor of degree 3 in $\mathbb{P}^{2}$; 2. $\sigma\in\operatorname{Aut}(C)$; 3. $\mathcal{L}$ is a very ample line bundle of degree 3 on $C$. We say that it is regular if moreover $\mathcal{L}\otimes\left(\sigma^{*}\circ\sigma^{*}(\mathcal{L})\right)\cong% \sigma^{*}(\mathcal{L})\otimes\sigma^{*}(\mathcal{L}).$
Definition 8. We say that $E\in\mathcal{T}$ is an exceptional object if $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(E,E[m])\cong\begin{cases}k&m=0\\ 0&m\neq 0\end{cases}.$ A sequence $(E_{1},\dotsc,E_{n})$ of objects $E_{i}\in\mathcal{T}$ is an exceptional sequence if each $E_{i}$ is exceptional, and $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(E_{i},E_{j}[m])=0$ for all $i>j$ and $m$. It is said to be strong if moreover $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(E_{i},E_{j}[m])=0$ for all $m\neq 0$. It is said to be full if it generates the category $\mathcal{T}$, or equivalently $\mathcal{T}=\left\langle\langle E_{1}\rangle,\dotsc,\langle E_{n}\rangle\right\rangle.$ is a semiorthogonal decomposition.
Definition 37. Let $\mathcal{L}$ be an invertible $\mathcal{A}$-bimodule, which is moreover $\mathbb{Q}$-Cartier, i.e. $(\mathcal{L}^{\otimes n})^{\vee\vee}$ is again invertible for some $n$. Then $\mathcal{L}$ is ample if $\mathrm{R}^{q}\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}(\mathcal{A},(\mathcal{L}^{% \otimes k})^{\vee\vee}\otimes\mathcal{F})\cong\mathrm{H}^{q}(S,(\mathcal{L}^{% \otimes k})^{\vee\vee}\otimes\mathcal{F})$ is zero for $q\geq 1$ and $k\gg 0$, where the isomorphism is induced by applying the forgetful functor.
Definition 13. The signed braid group $\Sigma\mathrm{B}_{n}$ is the semidirect product $\mathrm{B}_{n}\rtimes(\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z})^{n}$, where $(\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z})^{n}$ acts on $\mathrm{B}_{n}$ by considering the quotient $\mathrm{B}_{n}\twoheadrightarrow\operatorname{Sym}_{n}$. As such, the signed braid group has $2n-1$ generators: • $n-1$ generators $\sigma_{1},\ldots,\sigma_{n-1}$, as for the braid group $\mathrm{B}_{n}$, • $n$ generators $\epsilon_{1},\ldots,\epsilon_{n}$, as for $(\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z})^{n}$. These generators satisfy the relations $\left\{\begin{aligned} \displaystyle\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j}&\displaystyle=\sigma_% {j}\sigma_{i}&\displaystyle|i-j|\geq 2\\ \displaystyle\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}\sigma_{i}&\displaystyle=\sigma_{i+1}\sigma% _{i}\sigma_{i+1}&\displaystyle i=1,\dotsc,n-2\\ \displaystyle\epsilon_{i}^{2}&\displaystyle=1\\ \displaystyle\epsilon_{i}\epsilon_{j}&\displaystyle=\epsilon_{j}\epsilon_{i}\\ \displaystyle\epsilon_{i}\sigma_{i}\epsilon_{i+1}&\displaystyle=\sigma_{i}&% \displaystyle i=1,\dotsc,n-1.\end{aligned}\right.$
Definition 46. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a maximal order in a central simple algebra of degree 3 over the function field $K$ of a curve $X$ of genus $0$. If $\mathcal{A}$ is ramified in 3 points, with ramification degree 3 in each point, then we say that $\mathcal{A}$ is elliptic.
Definition 4.7. An EZ-category is a small category, equipped with a degree function from the set of objects to $\mathbb{N}$, such that (1) monomorphisms preserve (resp. raise) the degree if and only if they are invertible (resp. non-invertible); (2) every morphism factors as a split epimorphism followed by a monomorphism; (3) any pair of split epimorphisms with common domain has a strong pushout.
Definition 5.1. An object $\mathsf{K}\in\mathtt{sSet}^{\Gamma^{\operatorname{op}}}$ (resp. $\in\mathtt{sSet}^{\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}^{\operatorname{op}}}$) is called a Segal (wheeled) properad if the following hold: • $\mathsf{K}$ is Reedy fibrant, • $\mathsf{K}(\uparrow)=\Delta^{0}$, and • for all4Technically, if we are working in $\Gamma$ we do not yet have Segal maps associated to $G={\uparrow}$ or $G=C_{(n;m)}$ – this is not particularly relevant, as the Segal core inclusions should just be isomorphisms in this case, so the Segal map is even an isomorphism. graphs $G$, the Segal map $\epsilon_{G}:\mathsf{K}(G)\to\operatorname{map}(\operatorname{Sc}[G],\mathsf{K})$ is a weak equivalence of simplicial sets.
Definition 4.1. Suppose $\mathsf{K}\in\mathtt{Set}^{\Gamma^{\operatorname{op}}}$ and $x\in\mathsf{K}(G)$. Then we say $x$ is degenerate if there exist a non-empty composition of codegeneracy maps $\sigma:\Gamma(G)\to\Gamma(G^{\prime})$ and $y\in\mathsf{K}(G^{\prime})$ such that $x=\sigma^{*}y.$ If no such pair $(\sigma,y)$ exists, then $x$ is said to be non-degenerate.
Definition 3.2. Define the degree of a graph $G\in\mathtt{Gr}^{\circlearrowright}_{\text{c}}$ to be $\deg(G)=\begin{cases}0&\text{if }G=\uparrow;\\ 1&\text{if }G=\bullet;\\ |\operatorname{Vt}(G)|+|\operatorname{Edge_{i}}(G)|+1&\text{otherwise.}\end{cases}$ In [10, 9.4.5], we defined two wide subcategories of $\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}$ as follows: • $\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}^{+}$ is the subcategory generated by all isomorphisms and coface maps • $\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}^{-}$ is the subcategory generated by all isomorphisms and codegeneracy maps.
Definition 2.2. We say $\mathsf{K}$ satisfies the wheeled properadic Segal condition if the wheeled properadic Segal map $\mathsf{K}(G)\cong\mathtt{Set}^{\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}^{\operatorname{op}}% }\left(\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[G],\mathsf{K}\right)\to\mathtt{Set}^{\Gamma_% {\circlearrowright}^{\operatorname{op}}}\left(\operatorname{Sc}[G],\mathsf{K}\right)$ is a bijection for every $G\in\mathtt{Gr}^{\circlearrowright}_{\text{c}}$.
Definition 2.1. Suppose that $G$ is in $\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}$. (1) Let $B_{G}$ be the category whose set of objects is $\operatorname{Vt}(G)\amalg\operatorname{Edge}(G)$ with non-identity morphisms $\displaystyle e$ $\displaystyle\overset{\operatorname{in}}{\longrightarrow}v$ when $e$ is an input of $v$ $\displaystyle e$ $\displaystyle\overset{\operatorname{out}}{\longrightarrow}v$ when $e$ is an output of $v$. There is a functor $F:B_{G}\to\mathtt{Set}^{\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}^{\operatorname{op}}}$ with $\displaystyle F(e)$ $\displaystyle=\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[\uparrow]$ $\displaystyle F(e\overset{\operatorname{in}}{\longrightarrow}v)$ $\displaystyle=(\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[\uparrow]\xrightarrow{\operatorname{% in}_{e}}\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[C_{v}])$ $\displaystyle F(v)$ $\displaystyle=\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[C_{v}]$ $\displaystyle F(e\overset{\operatorname{out}}{\longrightarrow}v)$ $\displaystyle=(\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[\uparrow]\xrightarrow{\operatorname{% out}_{e}}\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[C_{v}])$ Define the wheeled properadic Segal core $\operatorname{Sc}[G]\in\mathtt{Set}^{\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}^{\operatorname% {op}}}$ as the colimit of the functor $F$. (2) Denote by $\operatorname{Sc}[G]\xrightarrow{\epsilon_{G}}\Gamma_{\circlearrowright}[G]$ the map induced by the subgraph inclusions $\displaystyle C_{v}$ $\displaystyle\to G$ $\displaystyle\uparrow_{e}$ $\displaystyle\to G,$ and call it the wheeled properadic Segal core map.
Definition 3.1. A generalized Reedy structure on a small category $\mathcal{R}$ consists of • wide subcategories $\mathcal{R}^{+}$ and $\mathcal{R}^{-}$, and • a degree function $\deg:\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{R})\to\mathbb{N}$ satisfying the following four axioms. (i) Non-invertible morphisms in $\mathcal{R}^{+}$ (resp., $\mathcal{R}^{-}$) raise (resp., lower) the degree. Isomorphisms in $\mathcal{R}$ preserve the degree. (ii) $\mathcal{R}^{+}\cap\mathcal{R}^{-}=\operatorname{Iso}(\mathcal{R})$. (iii) Every morphism $f$ of $\mathcal{R}$ factors as $f=gh$ with $g\in\mathcal{R}^{+}$ and $h\in\mathcal{R}^{-}$, and this factorization is unique up to isomorphism. (iv) If $\theta f=f$ for $\theta\in\operatorname{Iso}(\mathcal{R})$ and $f\in\mathcal{R}^{-}$, then $\theta$ is an identity. If, morever, the condition (iv’) If $f\theta=f$ for $\theta\in\operatorname{Iso}(\mathcal{R})$ and $f\in\mathcal{R}^{+}$, then $\theta$ is an identity holds, then we call this a generalized dualizable Reedy structure.
Definition 2. Let $X$ be a topological space. We say that $A\subseteq X$ is fundamental if i) $A$ is a non-empty and open-compact set, or ii) $A=\emptyset$ and for every non-empty collection $\mathcal{A}$ of non-empty open-compact sets whose intersection is empty, there exists a finite subcollection of $\mathcal{A}$ with empty intersection. We denote $\mathfrak{F}\left(X\right)$ the collection of fundamental subsets of $X$.
Definition 5. For each strongly continuous function $f:X\rightarrow Y$ between RA-spaces we define $\mathfrak{F}\left(f\right):\mathfrak{F}\left(Y\right)\rightarrow\mathfrak{F}% \left(X\right)$ by $\mathfrak{F}\left(f\right)\left(F\right)=f^{\ast}\left(F\right)$ and for each proper homomorphism $h:L\rightarrow M$ between distributive lattices we define $\mathfrak{spec}\left(h\right):\mathfrak{spec}\left(M\right)\rightarrow% \mathfrak{spec}\left(L\right)$ by $\mathfrak{spec}\left(h\right)\left(I\right)=h^{\ast}\left(I\right).$
Definition 1. A topological space is almost-sober if every proper irreducible closed set is the closure of some point4This notion is not taken from the literature. The notions of semi-sober and quasi-sober are found for example in [6] and [7] respectively, but their meanings are different..
Definition 3. We say that a topological space $X$ is an RA-space if $X$ is coherent and $\mathfrak{F}(X)$ is a sub-lattice of $\mathcal{\wp}(X).$
Definition 4. A space is up-spectral if it is coherent and sober. A space is down-spectral if it is $T_{0}$, coherent, compact and almost-sober. (See [6]).
Definition 2.1. Let ${\bf 2}$ be the category with two objects, called $0$ and $1$, and a single non-identity arrow $0\rightarrow 1$. Consider the functor category ${\bf Set}^{{\bf 2}^{\it op}}$. Explicitly, an object of this category is a triple $A=(A_{0},A_{1},a)$, where $A_{0},A_{1}$ are sets and $a:A_{1}\to A_{0}$ is a function. A morphism $f:A\to B$ is a commutative diagram \Addop@@ 2pc@C-1exA_1 \xy@@ix@
Definition 3.2 Let $({\cal C},p)$ and $({\cal C}^{\prime},p^{\prime})$ be universe categories with locally cartesian closed and binary product structures and let $(P,\widetilde{P})$, $(P^{\prime},\widetilde{P}^{\prime})$ be pre-$(P,\widetilde{P})$-structures on $p$ and $p^{\prime}$ respectively. A universe category functor ${\bf\Phi}=(\Phi,\phi,\widetilde{\phi})$ is said to be a pre-$(P,\widetilde{P})$-functor relative to the structures $(P,\widetilde{P})$ and $(P^{\prime},\widetilde{P}^{\prime})$ if the squares $\begin{CD}\Phi(I_{p}(U))@>{\Phi(P)}>{}>\Phi(U)\\ @V{\xi_{{\bf\Phi},1}}V{}V@V{}V{\phi}V\\ I_{p^{\prime}}(U^{\prime})@>{P^{\prime}}>{}>U^{\prime}\end{CD}{\,\,\,\,\,\,\,}% {\,\,\,\,\,\,\,}{\,\,\,\,\,\,\,}\begin{CD}\Phi(I_{p}(\widetilde{U}))@>{\Phi(% \widetilde{P})}>{}>\Phi(\widetilde{U})\\ @V{\widetilde{\xi}_{{\bf\Phi},1}}V{}V@V{}V{\widetilde{\phi}}V\\ I_{p^{\prime}}(\widetilde{U}^{\prime})@>{\widetilde{P}^{\prime}}>{}>\widetilde% {U}^{\prime}\end{CD}$ commute. If $(P,\widetilde{P})$ and $(P^{\prime},\widetilde{P}^{\prime})$ are $(P,\widetilde{P})$-structures then $\bf\Phi$ satisfying the above condition is called a $(P,\widetilde{P})$-functor.
Definition 2.2 Let $\cal C$ be a locally cartesian closed category with a binary product structure and $p:\widetilde{U}\rightarrow U$ a universe in $\cal C$. A pre-$(P,\widetilde{P})$-structure on $p$ is a pair of morphisms $\widetilde{P}:I_{p}(\widetilde{U})\rightarrow\widetilde{U}$ $P:I_{p}(U)\rightarrow U$ such that the square $\begin{CD}I_{p}(\widetilde{U})@>{\widetilde{P}}>{}>\widetilde{U}\\ @V{I_{p}(p)}V{}V@V{}V{p}V\\ I_{p}(U)@>{P}>{}>U\end{CD}$ commutes. A pre-$(P,\widetilde{P})$-structure is called a $(P,\widetilde{P})$-structure if the square (2) is a pullback.
Definition 2.1 Let $CC$ be a C-system. A pre-$(\Pi,\lambda)$-structure on $CC$ is a pair of morphisms of presheaves $\Pi:{\mathcal{O}b}_{2}\rightarrow{\mathcal{O}b}_{1}$ $\lambda:{\widetilde{\mathcal{O}b}}_{2}\rightarrow{\widetilde{\mathcal{O}b}}_{1}$ such that the square $\begin{CD}{\widetilde{\mathcal{O}b}}_{2}@>{\lambda}>{}>{\widetilde{\mathcal{O}% b}}_{1}\\ @V{\partial}V{}V@V{}V{\partial}V\\ {\mathcal{O}b}_{2}@>{\Pi}>{}>{\mathcal{O}b}_{1}\end{CD}$ commutes. A pre-$(\Pi,\lambda)$-structure is called a $(\Pi,\lambda)$-structure if the square (1) is a pullback.
Definition 3.1 Let $H:CC\rightarrow CC^{\prime}$ be a homomorphism of C-systems. Let $(\Pi,\lambda)$ and $(\Pi^{\prime},\lambda^{\prime})$ be pre-$(\Pi,\lambda)$-structures on $CC$ and $CC^{\prime}$ respectively. Then $H$ is called a $(\Pi,\lambda)$-homomorphism if the following two squares commute $\begin{CD}{\mathcal{O}b}_{2}@>{\Pi}>{}>{\mathcal{O}b}_{1}\\ @V{H{\mathcal{O}b}_{2}}V{}V@V{}V{H{\mathcal{O}b}_{1}}V\\ H^{\circ}({\mathcal{O}b}_{2})@>{H^{\circ}(\Pi^{\prime})}>{}>H^{\circ}({% \mathcal{O}b}_{1})\end{CD}{\,\,\,\,\,\,\,}{\,\,\,\,\,\,\,}{\,\,\,\,\,\,\,}{\,% \,\,\,\,\,\,}\begin{CD}\widetilde{{\mathcal{O}b}}_{2}@>{\lambda}>{}>\widetilde% {{\mathcal{O}b}}_{1}\\ @V{H\widetilde{{\mathcal{O}b}}_{2}}V{}V@V{}V{H\widetilde{{\mathcal{O}b}}_{1}}V% \\ H^{\circ}(\widetilde{{\mathcal{O}b}}_{2})@>{H^{\circ}(\lambda^{\prime})}>{}>H^% {\circ}(\widetilde{{\mathcal{O}b}}_{1})\end{CD}$ If $(\Pi,\lambda)$ and $(\Pi^{\prime},\lambda^{\prime})$ are $(\Pi,\lambda)$-structures then $H$ is called a $(\Pi,\lambda)$-homomorphism if it is a $(\Pi,\lambda)$-homomorphism with respect to the corresponding pre-$(\Pi,\lambda)$-structures.
Definition 2.10 Let $\cal C$ be an lcc category and let $p_{i}:\widetilde{U}_{i}\rightarrow U_{i}$, $i=1,2,3$ be three morphisms in $\cal C$. A $(P,\widetilde{P})$-structure on $(p_{1},p_{2},p_{3})$ is a pullback of the form $\begin{CD}I_{p_{1}}(\widetilde{U}_{2})@>{\widetilde{P}}>{}>\widetilde{U}_{3}\\ @V{I_{p_{1}}(p_{2})}V{}V@V{}V{p_{3}}V\\ I_{p_{1}}(U_{2})@>{P}>{}>U_{3}\end{CD}$
Definition 2.12 Let $\cal C$ be a category. A universe structure on a morphism $p:\widetilde{U}\rightarrow U$ in $\cal C$ is a mapping that assigns to any morphism $f:X\rightarrow U$ in $\cal C$ a pullback of the form $\begin{CD}(X,f)@>{Q(F)}>{}>\widetilde{U}\\ @V{p_{X,F}}V{}V@V{}V{p}V\\ X@>{F}>{}>U\end{CD}$ A universe in $\cal C$ is a morphism together with a universe structure on it.
Definition 4.1 A binary product diagram is a pair of morphisms of the form $(pr_{1}:bp\rightarrow X,pr_{2}:bp\rightarrow Y)$ such that for all $A\in{\cal C}$ the function $Mor_{\cal C}(A,bp)\rightarrow Mor_{\cal C}(A,X)\times Mor_{\cal C}(A,Y)$ given by $a\mapsto(a\circ pr_{1},a\circ pr_{2})$ is a bijection. The structure of binary products on $\cal C$ is a family, parametrized by pairs of objects $(X,Y)\in{\cal C}\times{\cal C}$, of binary product diagrams $(pr_{1}(X,Y):bp(X,Y)\rightarrow X,pr_{2}(X,Y):bp(X,Y)\rightarrow Y)$.
Definition 4.10 A locally cartesian closed structure on a category $\cal C$ is a family of (binary) cartesian closed structures on the categories ${\cal C}/Z$ for all $Z\in{\cal C}$. We usually denote the binary product on ${\cal C}/Z$ as above. We usually denote the internal-hom objects in ${\cal C}/Z$ by $\underline{Hom}_{Z}((X,f),(Y,g))$ and the canonical morphisms from $\underline{Hom}_{Z}((X,f),(Y,g))$ to $Z$ by $f\triangle g$. The rest of the notations ($\underline{Hom}_{Z}((X,f),b^{g})$, $ev^{(X,f)}_{(Y,g)}$, $adj^{(W,h),(X,f)}_{(Y,g)}$, $\underline{Hom}_{Z}(a^{f},(Y,g))$) immediately follow from the ones introduced previously. A locally cartesian closed category is a category together with a locally cartesian closed structure on it.
Definition 4.4 The (binary) cartesian closed structure on a category $\cal C$ is a collection of data of the form: 1. the structure of a category with binary products on $\cal C$, 2. for all $X,Y\in{\cal C}$ an object $\underline{Hom}(X,Y)$, 3. for all $X$ and $b:Y\rightarrow Y^{\prime}$ a morphism $\underline{Hom}(X,b):\underline{Hom}(X,Y)\rightarrow\underline{Hom}(X,Y^{% \prime})$ such that for all $Y$ one has $\underline{Hom}(X,Id_{Y})=Id_{\underline{Hom}(X,Y)}$ and for all $b:Y\rightarrow Y^{\prime}$, $b^{\prime}:Y^{\prime}\rightarrow Y^{\prime\prime}$ one has $\underline{Hom}(X,b\circ b^{\prime})=\underline{Hom}(X,b)\circ\underline{Hom}(% X,b^{\prime})$ 4. For all $X,Y$ a morphism $ev^{X}_{Y}:\underline{Hom}(X,Y)\times X\rightarrow Y$ such that for all $W$ the function $adj^{W,X}_{Y}:Mor(W,\underline{Hom}(X,Y))\rightarrow Mor(W\times X,Y)$ given by $u\mapsto(u\times Id_{X})\circ ev^{X}_{Y}$ is a bijection and such that for all $b:Y\rightarrow Y^{\prime}$ the square $\begin{CD}\underline{Hom}(X,Y)\times X@>{ev^{X}_{Y}}>{}>Y\\ @V{\underline{Hom}(X,b)\times Id_{X}}V{}V@V{}V{b}V\\ \underline{Hom}(X,Y^{\prime})\times X@>{ev^{X}_{Y^{\prime}}}>{}>Y^{\prime}\end% {CD}$ commutes. A cartesian closed category is a category together with a cartesian closed structure on it.
